description.text:
Clip to allow a TO92 temperature sensor to be firmly attached to a piece of 15mm water pipe for temperature monitoring.
tube part of clip allows space for cable connections and to be filled with e.g. epoxy to seal. Anulus at the cable end acts as a basic cable relief.
leaving the device slightly proud of the inner circumference of the clip will ensure that the device touches the pipe - maybe a bit of heat transfer paste will further aid the contact.
Can be edited in the original public file at OnShape (search for "18B20 holders")

Printer:

Kossel XL

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1mm layers, 0.2 width

Infill:

25%

Notes:

print such that the tube is horizontal so that the bending forces on the clip are within the layers. Any other sense will risk the clip delaminating when it is pushed around a piece of pipe.
Fill of only 25% is recommended to allow some flexibility to the clip arms - although I didn't try, I suspect a higher percentage fill will result in an arm breaking when forcing it around a piece of pipe.
Support inside the tube is recommended mainly to ensure that the TO92 'D' section is a reasonably accurate form.
The .stl allowed me to print and fit the TO92 case into the hole as a comfortable fit, not tight. Adjust as necessary by increase/decrease the percentage scaling of the object - the other dimensions are noit so critical that a slight change will cause a problem.

description.text:
The Calibron Twelve Block Puzzle is an apparently simple bin-packing puzzle credited to Theodore Edison in 1933 and originally marketed by his company, Calibron. The goal is simply to arrange all the pieces so that they form a rectangle (hint: make a 56x56 unit square). However, difficulty of this puzzle is rated 5/5!

There have been a lot of variants of this puzzle; in fact, there's one on Thingiverse as I write this -- but don't look at that because it shows the solution. My Calibron 12 was designed from scratch to take advantage of what 3D printers can do. The raised dimensions on each "block" are accurate in units of 2mm (with allowance for printing tolerance), so the puzzle fits in a 3D-printed box that is less than 3"x2"x1" -- but the pieces are big enough to handle easily.

description.text: Learning to design.

The Cloneboy is a kit that allows you to make a mold of... a certain masculine body part.  I hope this is okay here as this item is not explicit, nor is the name of the product it is designed for.  
When using the kit, you're asked to slit the plastic tube of the packaging, re-tape it to 6 cm in diameter, and then put a rubber ring over the end... and the packaging is thin plastic and it just collapses in an irregular fashion, and clearly will not work to make a good mold.  
So this is just a very very simple ring with an outer diameter of 6 cm to fit inside the tube at one end, to keep it from collapsing before you put the black rubber thing on that end.  Also lets you easily size the tube to exactly 6 cm without having to measure.  Works great for its intended purpose, and prints in about 5 minutes at .4 mm layer height.

Recently in my country was developed a house of experiments, where children accompanied by their parents or students can take part to an experiment.
One of them which my eyes was attracted by, it was the hyperbolic table experiment where a line cross a vertical red glass with a hyperbolic cut design on it.

hyperbolic table support table

Objectives

Design and create 3D printed object in Solidworks
Build complex designs from simple sketches to mathematical functions.
Explore the beauty of mathematics in a practical way.
You may believe when you look at a straight rod when it cross a hyperbolic slot to fail moving forward. But using math you can create a relation between a hyperbolic function and the length of a rod, in such a way the rod shall cross the slot on the other side in rotation through the middle of it.

Audiences

Anyone of any age that is familiar with 3D modeling and is getting started with more advanced options in Solidworks.
Students from high school or college can use this project to learn how to apply mathematical functions in 3D modeling.

Preparation

Students will need access to computers with Solidworks installed on them.
The students already should be familiar with design software and should know how to design simple objects from references.

Step 1: Buy non-printed parts

For rotation of the rod and to fix the table you will need 2 bearings of 608 model and 2 screws of 4x20 mm.

Step 2: Choose the hyperbolic function

The most important thing of this experiment is to choose the function that will draw the hyperbolic path. After that it is up to student how wide and long shall be the table and the rod.

Notice that the wide of the rod should be less with few millimeters, usually 2-3 mm, for a better crossing through the slot.

Step 3: Design

Design the parts based on the section "How I designed this" and notice to step 5.

Step 4: Check design

Before printing it is very important to check the design using Solidworks moving visualization to see if the rod is intersect with hyperbolic slot. If not the you can take to the next step, else student must correct either the length of the rod or the angle after that it spins.

Step 5: Printing

Before printing it is very important to check dimensions of the printer table.

The best way is to establish hyperbolic table edges based on printer table dimensions.

Results

Each student should have understand how to use functions in Solidworks and how mathematics can be fun.

description.text:
Finger tight?!?! Is that that british or imperial units? What does that mean exactly? My 2 year old can do finger tight that breaks some things, she is insanely strong!

These wrenches, size 1/2, and 7/16 inches, should yield at the calculated torque shown. 10 inch pounds of force, is not a lot, so I think finger tight would be around this amount. Imagine applying 1 pound of force to one end of a ruler, the force on the other end of the ruler is 12 pounds. Physics is awesome!

They are also plastic, and very light weight. NASA, U.S. Military, I'm thinking of you. Wouldn't it be great to have lightweight disposable tools in space? Yes, it would! Wouldn't it be great to reduce the amount of weight a soldier needs to carry? Yes, it would!

P.S. I calculated the torque required for the plastic to yield, based on PLA, not Nylon based filament. This is only an estimate.

This can be used to control the water main to your house, if the valve has a rectangular knob no larger than 35 mm by 15 mm and you have at least 50 mm of clearance all around the knob. Our valve is close to a basement wall and behind an access panel, which makes maneuvering a regular pipe wrench very difficult, and use of a street key impossible.

It still takes some force to operate, so be prepared to use both hands. A lanyard loop is included so you can hang it from a hook or use a string to attach it to the meter/valve so it won't wander too far or get dropped behind the wall.

To avoid gaps in the infill with Slic3r, I had to set vertical shells (perimeters) to 20, and set the bottom horizontal shells (solid layers) to the total number of layers (60 @ .2mm layer height), with 100% infill. The one shown is printed in HatchBox red/orange PLA. It took about 5 hours to print at 35 mm/s.

title: LED lamp parameterized including source code

description.text:
I wanted to create a cool designed LED-stripe lamp with three arms, 1.5m high for the living room to impress my wife what may be done with a 3D printer (20 cm bed size).
The lighted arms should start in the base (where the power supply is plugged in), turning around like a bow. To get a hight of up to 1.5m, I had to cut the arms into several pieces, each a maximum length of 20cm. Each piece had the width to take at least one LED stripe. To let the light shine through, the topping of each piece is made of clear PLA.
After printing you have to plug (and glue) the pieces together and put a stripe of LED inside.

I made a first test lamp with a height of 5cm. Works fine. Than I started a real lamp test with a 30cm lamp. Works also great (see pictures). I wanted to start the real lamp with a height of 1.5m...
...but my wife don't wanted to have 'plastics' in her living room! :-(
So the last proof of concept is missing, yet. May you can try this and show me how it works?

Just exchange the parameters 'Durchm' (height of the lamp in mm) and 'AnzElem' (Count of faces). 'Dicke' is for the amount of material for the arms, LedB and LedH are for the width and height of your LED stripe. All angles (and other parameters) will be calculated automatically from this. Have fun with printing this...

This is my take on a 3d printable wankel rotary engine with custom designed rounded gears for easy printing. While there are other wankel engines on here I don't like how they use standard involute gears on 3d prints because they have sharp corners that don't tend to be strong so I created one with rounded gears that print much stronger and faster. The other reason I made this was because I got bored and its a great way to learn a CAD software...

If you would like to see it animated check that out here

There are a few different turning mechanisms that I designed but all configurations require you to print the HOUSING+BASE and the ROTOR and the ECCENTRIC DRIVE. For turning mechanisms you can make

AXLE and HANDLE
or
AXLE and FINGER TURN
or the
TURN KNOB

The TURN KNOB or AXLE should be printed with a much higher infill percentage then the rest of the parts.

All parts have been printed at least twice by me and tweaked for better printing. I fixed the parts together using 5 minute epoxy being careful where it ended up.

If you do make one please post some pictures of how it turned out. Feel free to let me know if you run into any issues while printing.

description.text: These motorcycle/mountain bike combo wheel chocks were designed and made for the Nissan Utili-track system (though they might fit other track systems as well). They will securely hold a standard size motocross/dual-sport front tire, as well as a standard mountain bike tire in the center channel (you still tie bikes down). To finish them after printing, tear supports from bottom, and then use 3/4 to 1-inch long 3/8" (16 thread) bolts with flanges or washers with 3/8 spring nuts (found in electrical depts. of Home Depot). I cut the springs in half and fold them around to be on the other side so the channels will line up and lock in and the spring keeps it all tension-ed and together (see pictures). A 14mm socket tightens it all down, and then it's time to roost. The pictures are of the original prototype with a wider channel (too wide) for the mountain bike tire, which has since been reduced to hold mountain bike tires more securely.

title: screwed sleeve bearings - replacing LM8UU, LM10UU

description.text:
My K8200 started juddering. The linear bearings LM8UU, LM10UU from China had never really done a good job. So I didn't want to replace them with just another set of junk before trying printed sleeve bearings first.

IGUS design is famous, but I never understood, why it is not using helical grooves to get more stiffness into the sleeve cylinder. So I designed my own set of screwed sleeve bearings, and share them with this post.

The STL file I offer for download contains

  • 4 bearings replacing LM8UU with a height of 17.5 mm and diameters = 15.0/8.0 mm
  • 4 bearings replacing LM10UU with a height of 18.5 mm and diameters = 19.0/10.0 mm

To customize height and the two radii to your needs, just go into the SCAD file. Because of the helical design the number of tracks is not really important. I used 6 and a twist of 240° to be able to do the print without having to use support.

Printer:

K8200

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

Notes:

I did the print with PLA. As my printer is well calibrated the bearings came out ideally - a little tick too tight. To grind them to the right clearance, I used 8.0 mm and 10.0 mm drill bits with the drill slowly turning in REVERSED (!) direction. Finally I put some aceton on the rod to seal the contact areas. Clearance is best, if no slip and stick is noticable any more.
For lube I used silicon grease. Don't use ordinary grease or oil. Thermoplasts don't like that.

The original files are a stack of images from an MRI scan. The downloaded MRi data file comes as an .nii native format from the Brain Catalogue website (http://braincatalogue.org/Chimpanzee). This filetype can be opened in NIH Image (https://imagej.nih.gov/nih-image/), then converted to an image sequence. Install and use the Volume viewer plugin (https://imagej.nih.gov/ij/plugins/volume-viewer.html) display as a surface (threshold at about 50 usually works well to get rid of artifacts) and then Export Surfaces as binary stl.

There will be some cleanup necessary - I used Rhino 3D v 5 to get rid of extraneous extra bits and the Meshmixer repair stl commands to fix inverted normals until we arrive at this model. I have not printed it yet but it should be printable with a raft and supports.

title: Pedals for lowboy quad para-glider foot ground steering.

description.text:
3D printed pedals for my lowboy quad para-glider.
Pedals clamp onto the 25mm foot steering bar.
They are angled in at 7.5 degrees and a lot more comfortable than the round bar.
Two versions are provided - one flat and one with texture.
M3 screws and knurl nuts screw the pieces together.
Mine are printed in PETG with 90% fill.
Update.
I've also printed one with carbon fibre ABS. It looks good but I'm not sure if it is any better than PETG. I will try it when one of the PETG versions break.
I also printed a TPU cover. This might have slightly better grip.
The cover stretches over and snaps into place. I used a flat screwdriver bladed to lever it on.
NB - there is support material around the grove in the cover which must be removed.
Punching a hole through the support and grabbing it with pointy pliers allows it to be peeled off.
Some other elastomer may work instead of TPU.
